  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Abel Seymour Cunningham</name>
    <description><![CDATA[Evergreen Cemetery, Red River &amp; N. Vine Sts. (Section 1, Lot 42-47)<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> Victoria<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Soldier in the Texas War for Independence Soldier, Ranger and Congressman Republic of Texas. Erected by the State of Texas, 1962.]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.009555,28.811463,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Band Stand</name>
    <description><![CDATA[Constitution Square, Main &amp; Constitution Sts., Victoria<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> Main &amp; Constitution Sts., in Memorial Plaza, Victoria<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Originally built before 1885, on Constitution Street side of the public square, for public gatherings and concerts. Moved to center of public square and placed upon foundation of the old standpipe in 1923. Completely restored in 1962 by Mr. and Mrs. J.M. Pickering. Recorded Texas Historic Landmark - 1964]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.006672,28.799329,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Beck Ranch Headquarters</name>
    <description><![CDATA[<b>Address:</b> 412 Magruder Dr., Victoria<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> German native Charles (Carl) August Beck (1810-1885) purchased forty acres at this site in 1862. Ten years later he built this Greek Revival home as a wedding gift for his son Charles Theodore Beck (b. 1846). This house served as the headquarters for their cattle ranch which eventually grew to about 25,000 acres. In 1923 it became the center of Arthur Yariger's dairy business and has remained in the Yariger Family since that date. Recorded Texas Historic Landmark - 1980]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.003172,28.842748,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Billy Kyle Ranch House</name>
    <description><![CDATA[From Nursery, take US 87 NW about 1/4 mile, go west at first cattleguard.  Follow private road west about 1/4 mile (Private).<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 0.25 mi. NW on US 87; 0.25 mi. W on private ranch road, Nursery<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Texas Colonial ranch home. Built 1872 by W.H. "Uncle Billy" Kyle (1836-1907), trail driver, cattleman, Civil War veteran. Recorded Texas Historic Landmark - 1965]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.10806,28.926477,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
